                      "name": "title",
                      "fill": "#1E3322",
                      "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                      "width": "fill_container",
                      "content": "The Art of Minimalist Design: Less is More",
                      "lineHeight": 1.3,
                      "fontFamily": "Inter",
                      "fontSize": 28,
                      "fontWeight": "600"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "frame",
                      "id": "cxjYI",
                      "name": "Meta Row",
                      "gap": 16,
                      "alignItems": "center",
                      "children": [
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "id": "2z2Oy",
                          "name": "pubDate",
                          "fill": "$--muted-foreground",
                          "content": "March 15, 2026",
                          "fontFamily": "Inter",
                          "fontSize": 13,
                          "fontWeight": "normal"
                        },
                        {
                          "type": "ellipse",
                          "id": "okbtl",
                          "name": "dotSep",
                          "fill": "$--muted-foreground",
                          "width": 4,
                          "height": 4
                        },
                        {
                          "type": "frame",
                          "id": "EOHjK",
                          "name": "viewGroup",
                          "gap": 6,
                          "alignItems": "center",
                          "children": [
                            {
                              "type": "icon_font",
                              "id": "Db6ED",
                              "name": "eyeIcon",
                              "width": 14,
                              "height": 14,
                              "iconFontName": "eye",
                              "iconFontFamily": "lucide",
                              "fill": "$--muted-foreground"
                            },
                            {
                              "type": "text",
                              "id": "Cliji",
                              "name": "viewCount",
                              "fill": "$--muted-foreground",
                              "content": "1,247 views",
                              "fontFamily": "Inter",
                              "fontSize": 13,
                              "fontWeight": "normal"
                            }
                          ]
                        }
                      ]
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "w4rLv",
                  "name": "Hero Image",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "height": 360,
                  "fill": {
                    "type": "image",
                    "enabled": true,
                    "url": "./images/generated-1774761321711.png",
                    "mode": "fill"
                  },
                  "cornerRadius": 12
                },
                {
                  "type": "frame",
                  "id": "PbI97",
                  "name": "Post Body",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "layout": "vertical",
                  "gap": 20,
                  "children": [
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "XS94D",
                      "name": "p1",
                      "fill": "#1E3322",
                      "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                      "width": "fill_container",
                      "content": "In the world of design, the principle of minimalism has long been celebrated as a philosophy that strips away the unnecessary to reveal what truly matters. This approach, rooted in the belief that simplicity leads to clarity, has influenced everything from architecture to digital interfaces. When we embrace minimalism, we create space for the content itself to breathe and communicate directly with the viewer.",
                      "lineHeight": 1.7,
                      "fontFamily": "Inter",
                      "fontSize": 16,
                      "fontWeight": "normal"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "8eE3O",
                      "name": "p2",
                      "fill": "#1E3322",
                      "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                      "width": "fill_container",
                      "content": "The challenge of minimalist design lies not in removing elements, but in knowing which elements to keep. Every remaining piece must earn its place, serving a clear purpose in the overall composition. Typography becomes paramount — the choice of typeface, the rhythm of line spacing, and the weight of each word all carry increased significance when there are fewer visual elements competing for attention.",
                      "lineHeight": 1.7,
                      "fontFamily": "Inter",
                      "fontSize": 16,
                      "fontWeight": "normal"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "bBn5o",
                      "name": "p3",
                      "fill": "#1E3322",
                      "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                      "width": "fill_container",
                      "content": "Whitespace, often misunderstood as empty or wasted space, is in fact one of the most powerful tools in a minimalist designer's toolkit. It provides visual rest, creates hierarchy, and guides the reader's eye through the content with a calm, unhurried pace. The generous use of whitespace signals confidence — a willingness to let the work speak for itself without the need for constant visual stimulation.",
                      "lineHeight": 1.7,
                      "fontFamily": "Inter",
                      "fontSize": 16,
                      "fontWeight": "normal"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "id": "8dl9K",
                      "name": "p4",
                      "fill": "#1E3322",
                      "textGrowth": "fixed-width",
                      "width": "fill_container",
                      "content": "As we continue to navigate an increasingly noisy digital landscape, the value of restraint in design only grows. Minimalism is not about doing less for its own sake, but about being intentional with every choice. It is a commitment to clarity, to respect for the reader's time and attention, and to the enduring belief that good design disappears, leaving only the message behind.",
                      "lineHeight": 1.7,
                      "fontFamily": "Inter",
                      "fontSize": 16,
                      "fontWeight": "normal"
                    }
                  ]
                },
                {
                  "type": "rectangle",
                  "id": "nnWfY",
                  "name": "Divider",
                  "fill": "$--border",
                  "width": "fill_container",
                  "height": 1
                },
